body:
@natke please let me know what you think.

Technically, these two packages have some other slight differences:
1. The CPU one does not have C++ RTTI. GPU does.
2. The CPU one enables Link-Time Code Gen. The GPU one could do the same, but I haven't tried.
3. The CPU one use protobuf-lite, the GPU one use the full version of protobuf because TensorRT need it.
4. The CPU one can support ARM , the GPU one haven't.
5. The CPU one can support macOS , the GPU one doesn't. 

Things like this. For example, as long we still have a CPU package, I would not add macOS support to the GPU package. We will not be able to make CUDA working on macOS, I'm saying CPU-only. It makes no sense to make a GPU package without having GPU functionality. 

From technical perspective, the CPU package always has its unique value. But as you said, in most cases these things are not important. 

> Could it cause issues having both packages installed at once?

I believe so.
I think we don't need to emphasize the tiny differences.  From product point of view you may make the decision how we recommend the two packages to our users.

Thanks for the reply and details @snn. As a user, I think adding a line or two to https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/get-started/with-python.html should mention:
1. only install one of the two pip packages
2. the GPU package includes most CPU capabilities
3. stick to `onnxruntime` for ARM CPUs and/or macOS operating system
